sec.p:
The first reports of marine mollusks of the Persian Gulf and Gulf of Oman date back approximately to the middle part of the 19 th century. In a report from 1865, Issel describes the molluscan fauna from these areas and lists 17 marine species. During this time, Colonel Lewis Pelly collected shells in the Persian Gulf and Gulf of Oman region (likely between 1859-1872; https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lewis_Pelly) that later became part of the MacAndrew collection (at the Museum of Zoology at the University of Cambridge (
)). Specimens from Pelly’s collection were ultimately utilized by H.
and E.A. Smith (1872, 1875, 1877a, 1877b, 1882a, 1882b, 1884, 1888) to describe a variety of new species. The latter described 35 new species that were originally collected by Pelly; the types are stored in the Natural History Museum, London. In 1874 Martens published a paper on the shells collected mainly in the Persian Gulf near Bushehr (northwest Persian Gulf, Iran ) by Prof. Hausknecht, who collected 49 gastropod species, including several new ones. The most prolific person in terms of the amount of material collected from the area is certainly Townsend (1887–1948). He was involved in the repair of the telegraph cable that then ran through the Persian Gulf towards India and collected many specimens of mollusks including those from deep water sites. In a series of papers published between 1895 and 1928, Melvill and Standen report on much of Townsend’s material and describe approximately 600 new species, many of them of small size.
